## Quantification of metformin in human plasma

The analytical procedure involved modification of an extraction and {{ drug.molecular_formula }} method previously reported in the literature.20 A {{ drug.strength }}/mL stock {{ drug.dosage_form }} of metformin and cimetidine were prepared by dissolving {{ drug.strength }} of each in a {{ drug.strength }} volumetric flask using methanol, and the solutions were stored at {{ storage.temperature }}. The chromatographic system consisted of an Agilent 1,100 series liquid chromatography system (Agilent Technologies, United States) fitted with a quaternary pump and a diode array UV detector ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}; at 190–900 nm). Chromatographic separation was achieved at {{ storage.temperature }} on a reverse-phase Agilent Zorbax (C18) column (5 µm × 4.6 mm) while the mobile phase was acetonitrile-potassium hydrogen phosphate buffer (0.01 M, adjusted to pH 6.67), 55:45, applied at a flow rate of 1.{{ drug.strength }}/min. Sample was injected through a Rheodyne model 7725 valve (United States) fitted with a 20 µL loop.

The eluents were monitored with UV detection at 234 nm λmax, while chromatograms were recorded with HP Chemstation software. To 100 µL of plasma in a 2-mL Eppendorf tube was added 50 µL of {{ drug.strength }}/mL cimetidine {{ drug.dosage_form }} (internal standard), 100 µL of 8M {{ drug.molecular_formula }} and 1.{{ drug.strength }} of 1-butanol/n-hexane (50:50, v/v), followed by shaking for 2 min. After centrifugation at 10,{{ drug.strength }} for 5 min, the whole organic layer was separated and transferred into another tube. Metformin was back-extracted with 100 µL of 1% acetic acid. The mixture was vortex-mixed and centrifuged for 1 min. The organic phase was removed, and a 20 µL volume of aqueous phase was injected into the chromatograph. The peak area ratio for each sample was generated from the peak response of metformin and cimetidine using UV detection at 234 nm.

The assay was validated according to {{ drug.molecular_formula }} draft guidance ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}, 2013) to reflect acceptable linearity, sensitivity, specificity, accuracy and precision. Calibration curves were constructed within 0.{{ drug.strength }}/mL to 5.{{ drug.strength }}/mL, based on the relationship between the peak area ratios and the standard solutions of metformin. A 100 µL aliquot of drug-free plasma samples were spiked with 50 µL of internal standard {{ drug.dosage_form }} ({{ drug.strength }}/mL cimetidine) and standard solutions (between the range of 0.05–5.{{ drug.strength }}/mL) of metformin.

For each sample, the above-stated extraction procedure was carried out and the supernatant (20 µL) was injected into an {{ drug.molecular_formula }} column. A plot of peak area ratios versus concentrations of the standard solutions was made. The limit of detection ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) and limit of quantification ({{ drug.molecular_formula }}) were generated based on regression analysis of the calibration curve. Intra-day precision and accuracy were determined by analysis of five replicates of each QC level at 0.{{ drug.strength }}/mL, 0.{{ drug.strength }}/mL and 5.{{ drug.strength }}/mL concentrations. Inter-day precision was measured by analysis of duplicates of each QC concentration on three different days.
